    "body": "## Problem\n\n1. unclear guidance about performance strategy of vim.pos/vim.range\n2. `vim.treesitter` uses its own special Range4/Range6 shapes internally (and externally in some cases, e.g. `node:range() => Range4`) https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/d40875a2f844d0005441aa0db47599e2f6b63be1/runtime/lua/vim/treesitter/_range.lua#L10-L17\n\n\n<details><summary>Working assumptions</summary>\n<p>\n1. `vim.pos` needs \"offsets\", since that's part of `getpos()`.\n2. users should never have to deal with the special special TS `RangeX` types, or at least `vim.pos` should be able to convert them losslessly into something more usable\n3. `vim.treesitter` should accept `vim.pos` shapes at the \"edges\", even if it uses special `RangeX` types internally\n</p>\n</details> \n\n\n\n\n## Analysis\n\n\n- friendly fields (`__index` lookups) are about 2-3x slower in puc-lua or luajit-off\n- `vim.treesitter` uses raw `Range6` arrays for injected regions, including byte offsets*. Fast even on PUC-Lua.\n    - That shape matters because tree-sitter included ranges need row/col/byte tuples; vim.pos only carries row/col/buf.\n\n<details><summary>Stress Benchmark</summary>\n<p>\n\n    Tiny injections stress allocation volume\n    \n    Stress Benchmark\n    \n    Created/stored 100k tiny ranges:\n        Range6 raw arrays: 1.93ms, 17.4MiB\n        vim.range objects: 1.29ms, 12.0MiB with JIT on, but no byte offsets, so not equivalent\n        two vim.pos + wrapper: 3.24ms, 29.9MiB\n    With JIT off:\n        Range6 raw arrays: 2.65ms\n        vim.range objects: 6.88ms\n        two vim.pos + wrapper: 31.5ms\n\n</p>\n</details> \n\n## Proposal\n\nbased on @ofseed ([ref](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/38561#issuecomment-4326214346)) and @lewis6991 perf analysis, `vim.pos` and `vim.range` should be fine for treesitter (even internally, i.e. replace `Range4` / `Range6`), *if*:\n\n- `vim.range` learns bytes offsets and changes its layout. \n    - I.e. it needs to change its layout to match `Range6`. Then we can safely replace `Range6` with `vim.range`. (The metatable is low-cost; `vim.treesitter` only cares about the numeric indices.)",
